<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1545,2035]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,866,1545,1571]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">Erroneous geographical record to Neotropical Region.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[875,1185,1545,1570]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ciliatocosta">
<emphasis box="[875,1185,1545,1570]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">Elaphropeza ciliatocosta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,258,1584,1610]" name="Australia" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">Australia</collectingCountry>
(Brisbane), and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bezzi" box="[453,605,1584,1610]" pageId="12" pageNumber="45" refString="Bezzi, M. (1909) Beitrage zur Kenntniss der sudamerikanischen Dipterenfauna auf Grund der Sammelergebnisse einer Reise in Chile, Peru und Bolivia, ausgefuhrt in den Jahren 1902 - 1904 von W. Schnuse. Fam. Empididae. Nova Acta Academiae Caesareae Leopoldino-Carolinae Germanicae Naturae Curiosorum, Halle, 91, n. 3, 297 - 406." type="journal article" year="1909">
Bezzi (
<number box="[536,597,1584,1610]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" value="1909.0">1909</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
registered this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[906,992,1584,1610]" name="Bolivia" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(Maipiri). 
<bibRefCitation author="Rafael" box="[1122,1284,1584,1610]" pageId="12" pageNumber="46" refString="Rafael, J. A. (1995) Revisao das especies Neotropicais de Empididae (Diptera) descritas por Mario Bezzi. II. Tachydromiinae. Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 39, 733 - 739." type="journal article" year="1995">
Rafael (
<number box="[1214,1275,1584,1610]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" value="1995.0">1995</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
re-described this species based on Bezzi’s Bolivian exemplar since the 
<typeStatus box="[845,948,1622,1648]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">holotype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1022,1130,1622,1648]" name="Australia" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">Australia</collectingCountry>
was destroyed in 
<number box="[1347,1406,1622,1648]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" value="1956.0">1956</number>
at the Hungarian Natural History Museum (
<bibRefCitation author="Smith" box="[675,829,1661,1687]" pageId="12" pageNumber="46" refString="Smith, K. G. V. (1961) On the genus Macrostomus Wiedemann (Diptera: Empididae) with notes on the included species and new synonymy. Proceedings of the Royal Entomological Society of London, (B) 30 (3 - 4), 53 - 56." type="journal article" year="1961">
Smith 
<number box="[761,829,1661,1687]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" value="1961.0">1961</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). However, in the same paper, Rafael raises the possibility of the Bolivian exemplar analysed by him was different from that described from 
<collectingCountry box="[1235,1343,1700,1726]" name="Australia" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rafael" pageId="12" pageNumber="46" refString="Rafael, J. A. (1995) Revisao das especies Neotropicais de Empididae (Diptera) descritas por Mario Bezzi. II. Tachydromiinae. Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 39, 733 - 739." type="journal article" year="1995">
Rafael 
<number box="[151,215,1738,1764]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" value="1995.0">1995</number>
: 
<number box="[227,277,1738,1764]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44" value="737.0">737</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The Bolivian specimen agrees with the Australian 
<typeStatus box="[910,962,1738,1764]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">type</typeStatus>
description on the basis of color of the anterior region of the scutum and number of bristles on the hind tibia, but differ by having a dark postpedicel, black posterior region on scutum and black hind tibia. So, we believe the Bolivian identification was an error on Bezzi’s part and this is actually an undescribed species, and we exclude this Bolivian record from its geographical record. The Bolivian exemplar is quite damaged (head, all legs and left wing missing, scutum damaged, right wing in slide) and, although the abdomen with male terminalia is in a microvial, we prefer not to describe this new species at this time and wait for more exemplars to be obtained. A revision of Australian species is needed, at which time a 
<typeStatus box="[554,647,2009,2035]" pageId="12" pageNumber="44">neotype</typeStatus>
for this species can be designated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
